rect.title: Every object continues in its state of rest or constant velocity (ie constant speed i n a straight line) unless a net force acts on it to change that state.
When body A exerts a force on body B, body B exerts a force of the same type that is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction on body A.
The rate of change of momentum of a body is proportional to the net force acting on it, and this (rate of) change of momentum takes place in the direction of the net force.
The linear momentum of a body p is defined as the product of its mass and its velocity.
1.Draw a free-body diagram (FBD). 2.Indicate the direction of the acceleration with an arrow. 3.Resolve all the forces into the direction of the acceleration. 4.Substitute into Fnet = ma
The impulse of a force I is defined as the product of the force and the time t during which it acts.
For a system of interacting bodies, the total momentum of the bodies (i.e. momentum of the system) remains constant, provided no net force acts on the system.

The total kinetic energy is conserved ie total KE BEFORE = total KE AFTER the collision. DURING an elastic collision, some KE may be converted into elastic PE or electric PE (for charged particles) but the PE is eventually reconverted back to KE
